  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What's the size of a 4K image?",
  "response": "A **4K image** typically refers to its resolution, which denotes the number of pixels displayed horizontally and vertically. There are two main standards for 4K resolution:\n\n1. **Ultra High Definition (UHD) 4K:**\n   - **Resolution:** 3840 \u00d7 2160 pixels\n   - **Aspect Ratio:** 16:9\n   - **Usage:** Commonly used in consumer televisions, monitors, and streaming content.\n\n2. **DCI 4K:**\n   - **Resolution:** 4096 \u00d7 2160 pixels\n   - **Aspect Ratio:** Approximately 17:9\n   - **Usage:** Predominantly used in digital cinema and professional video production.\n\n**File Size Considerations:**\nThe actual file size of a 4K image can vary widely based on several factors:\n- **Image Format:** Formats like JPEG, PNG, RAW, or TIFF have different compression methods and efficiencies.\n- **Compression Level:** Higher compression (e.g., JPEG with high compression) reduces file size but may decrease image quality.\n- **Color Depth:** More bits per pixel (e.g., 8-bit vs. 16-bit) increase file size.\n- **Content Complexity:** Images with more detail and color variation generally result in larger file sizes, especially in lossless formats.\n\n**Approximate File Sizes:**\n- **JPEG (High Quality):** Around 5\u201315 MB\n- **PNG:** Typically between 10\u201330 MB\n- **RAW:** Can range from 20\u201350 MB or more, depending on the camera and settings\n- **TIFF (Uncompressed):** Often 30\u2013100 MB or higher\n\n**Physical Dimensions for Printing:**\nIf you're considering printing a 4K image, the physical size achievable without quality loss depends on the DPI (dots per inch):\n- **At 300 DPI (high quality):** Approximately 12.8 \u00d7 7.2 inches\n- **At 150 DPI (standard quality):** Approximately 25.6 \u00d7 14.4 inches\n\n**Summary:**\n- **Resolution:** 3840 \u00d7 2160 pixels (UHD) or 4096 \u00d7 2160 pixels (DCI)\n- **File Size:** Varies based on format, compression, and image content\n- **Print Size:** Depends on desired DPI, ranging from ~12\u00d77 inches at high quality to larger sizes at lower DPI\n\nIf you have a specific context in mind (e.g., digital display, printing, file storage), feel free to provide more details for a more tailored answer!",
